sec.p:
We first focus on the regime with partial sequestration, so at the time of transition to the carbon-free era, T, all energy consists of renewables, i.e.
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ m_{t} = 1 $$\end{document}
m t
= 1
for all t ≥ T, and not all emissions from burning fossil fuel are fully sequestrated yet, i.e.,
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ a_{t} < 1 $$\end{document}
a t
< 1
for all t < T. There is no need for sequestration in the carbon-free era, so that
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ a_{t} = 0 $$\end{document}
a t
= 0
for all t ≥ T. The following result summarises such a regime with partial sequestration.
